":"Chatwood","meanings":["English:  see  Chetwood  ."]},{"name":"Chetwood","meanings":["English: habitational name from Chetwode in Buckinghamshire or from Cheetwood in Cheetham, Manchester (Lancashire). This placename consists of the Brittonic placename element <i>cēto-</i> ‘wood’, with an explanatory addition in Old English of <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’. The surname may also be a Shropshire variant of   Chatwin  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Chetwode was born about 1415, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Chetwode, was 29 and his mother, Margerey Crewe, was 25. He married Isabel Noel about 1439, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1485, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 72."},"et":{"Abt 1415–Abt 1485":"umbes 1415–umbes 1485","1415–1485":"1415–1485","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1415":"1415","about 1439":"umbes 1439","1422, 1455, 1483, 1498":"1422","1388":"1388","Abt 1485":"umbes 1485","1497":"1497","about 1414":"umbes 1414","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1392":"1392","1419":"1419","Abt 1415":"umbes 1415","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worleston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worleston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1415–Abt 1485":"noin 1415–noin 1485","1415